SCOTS actor Richard McCabe has paid tribute to fellow Tony Award winner Dame Helen Mirren and dedicated his gong to ex-Prime Minister Harold Wilson after the Broadway co-stars each won the prestigious prize.McCabe was awarded best performance by an actor in a featured role in a play after starring as former Labour Prime Minister Harold Wilson in New York.McCabe, who was born in Glasgow to a Scots father, but grew up in Sussex, with his French mother following his father's death, trained at the Royal Academy of Dramatic Arts.He said: &quot;First and foremost, I would like to thank the great Helen Mirren who is as brilliant off stage frankly as she is on it.&quot;The actor who is an associate of the Royal Shakespeare Company also paid tribute to Mr Wilson in the drama which explores The Queen's relationship with her prime ministers.